The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Tata Motors posts robust numbers 

 OUR CORRESPONDENT 

 Tata Motors MD Ravi Kant (right) and executive director P.P. Kadle in Mumbai on Friday. (Fotocorp)

 Mumbai, May 19: Tata Motors registered a 24 per cent rise in profit after tax at Rs 1,528.88 crore for 2005-06 against Rs 1,236.95 crore in the previous year.

 The board of directors has recommended a dividend of Rs 13 on share of Rs 10 each, or 130 per cent, for financial year 2005-06, subject to shareholders approval.

 Though the stock moved up in anticipation of robust numbers to touch a high of Rs 913.40, the negative sentiments in the market hammered it to a days low of Rs 810. The scrip closed at Rs 848.90, down Rs 24. 

 Total revenues grew 18 per cent to Rs 20,602.20 crore from Rs 17,419.13 crore in the previous fiscal. Profit before tax rose 24 per cent at Rs 2,053.38 crore against Rs 1,651.90 crore in 2004-05. 

 The company registered its highest-ever overall sales of 4,52,129 vehicles last fiscal, up 14 per cent from 3,99,566 vehicles sold in the previous year. 

 The companys total market share in the commercial vehicles segment increased to 61.3 per cent from 59.7 per cent. In the domestic market, too, it registered highest ever sales of 2,14,836 units, a growth of 13 per cent. 

 Passenger vehicle sales in the domestic market stood at 1,89,070, a growth of 6 per cent. The company maintained a market share of 16.5 per cent in this segment. 

 Tata Motorss exports grew 65 per cent at 50,223 vehicles. It contributes 16 per cent to the total revenue of the company. 

 For the fourth quarter, the company has registered an 18 per cent growth in profit after tax at Rs 458.11 crore against Rs 388.17 crore for the same period previous fiscal. 

 Revenues grew 29 per cent at Rs 6,882.75 crore compared with Rs 5,338.87 crore a year ago. 

 Tata Motors will focus on east and north Africa along with West Asia and the CIS countries. Africa is one of the impressive markets. In South Africa, Tata has emerged as one of the emerging brands. We will be looking seriously at Turkey, West Asia and CIS countries, while Italy and Spain will remain as potential markets for passenger cars, said Ravi Kant, managing director.




